# Control Plane Incident Scenario

## Overview

Control plane issues typically involve CRUD operation failures on virtual machines (VM) or VM scale sets (VMSS). These failures can result in significant impacts on the infrastructure.

- **Incident Example 1:** [Incident-440639800](https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/incident/440639800/summary): CRUD operation failures for compute resources.

### How to Identify Control Plane Changes:

1. **Determine the fabric cluster or region involved in the incident.**

   - If the fabric cluster is known, enter it in the "EntityId" field (e.g., `uswestcentral-prod-a`).
2. **Navigate to Change Details View:**

   - [Change Details View](https://dataexplorer.azure.com/dashboards/d0357802-00ae-48c7-85a2-5cf02d98de77?p-_startTime=1hours&p-_endTime=now&p-_entityIds=all&p-_region=all&p-_availabilityZone=all&p-_datacenter=all&p-_cluster=all&p-_serviceName=v-Azure+Cosmos+DB&p-_icmTeamName=all&p-_source=all&p-_entityType=all&p-_veName=all&p-_payload=all&p-_payloadOwner=all#66cc3653-ecde-4c2c-9d24-1838d351d4d4)
3. **Clear any pre-set filters and input the fabric cluster in the EntityId field.**
4. **Set the timeline:**

   - Use a custom time range, ideally starting 24 hours prior to the incident.
5. **Analyze control plane changes:**

   - Review payload details, bypasses, and deployment status within the Change Details view.
6. **Further investigation:**

   - If needed, use the [Node View](https://dataexplorer.azure.com/dashboards/d0357802-00ae-48c7-85a2-5cf02d98de77?p-_nodeid=all&p-_entityTypeNode=all#08c31477-dfa3-43d3-9427-a6a57b228c43) to track changes applied at the node level.
